	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64319207"><p>168,032 vs 168,395 seems pretty close... <i>if US tech industry headcount in 2023 was the same as it was in 2001.  Which it wasn't.  A <a href="https://www2.deloitte.com/us/en/insights/economy/spotlight/tech-workforce-expanding.html" title="deloitte.com" rel="nofollow">Deloitte report</a> [deloitte.com] from 2021 indicates the industry grew from ~3.6 million workers in 2001 to ~5m+ in 2021.  So the 2023 layoffs affected a smaller percentage of the workforce.</i></p><p><i>Of course, that ~40% overall growth in industry headcount pales in comparison to the growth seen by MFAANG - 4x for Microsoft, 15x for Apple, 40x for Netflix, 50x for Meta (just since 2009), 600x for Google, and 2000x for Amazon.</i></p></div>
